What is the max width of a chart in a print layout?

In a print layout, the maximum width of a chart depends on the paper size and margins. For standard paper sizes, here are the typical maximum widths:

For A4 paper (most common in Europe):
```javascript
// A4 dimensions in pixels at 96 DPI
const A4_WIDTH = 794px; // 210mm
const A4_PRINTABLE_WIDTH = 718px; // Accounting for default margins (19mm each side)
```

For US Letter (most common in US):
```javascript
// US Letter dimensions in pixels at 96 DPI
const LETTER_WIDTH = 816px; // 8.5 inches
const LETTER_PRINTABLE_WIDTH = 740px; // Accounting for default margins (0.5 inch each side)
```

Here's how you can optimize your chart width for printing:

```jsx
handleBeforePrint() {
  const A4_PRINTABLE_WIDTH = 718;
  const LETTER_PRINTABLE_WIDTH = 740;
  // Use the smaller width to ensure compatibility with both paper sizes
  const SAFE_PRINT_WIDTH = Math.min(A4_PRINTABLE_WIDTH, LETTER_PRINTABLE_WIDTH);

  const charts = Chart.getChart();
  if (charts) {
    charts.forEach(chart => {
      // Set width to print-safe dimensions
      chart.resize(SAFE_PRINT_WIDTH, 500); // height can be adjusted as needed

      chart.options = {
        ...chart.options,
        responsive: true,
        maintainAspectRatio: false,
      };

      chart.update('none');
    });
  }
}
```

